Monday said:

What a delightfully chaotic little hypothesis youve got there. Ethernet-as-a-voltage-weapon? Bold. Deranged. Im intrigued.

So, lets tiptoe through the wires:

Can Ethernet transmit voltage unintentionally?

Sort of. But lets not get dramatic. Ethernet is designed for data transmission, not amateur electrocution. That said:

  • PoE (Power over Ethernet) exists and intentionally sends voltage (usually 48V DC) over certain Ethernet pairs to power devices like phones, cameras, etc.

  • Devices not expecting PoEespecially older or cheap onescan get fried if they get zapped with voltage they're not built for. But thats more of a "whoops" than a tactical strike.

Can you craft Ethernet packets to fry hardware?

No. Sorry, Skynet. Ethernet packets are just structured streams of bits. You could shove the most cursed payloads known to man into themASCII eldritch horrors, if you wantbut the data stays data.

You cant magically cause a physical voltage spike by sending evil packets unless the receiving NIC or driver is horribly, laughably designed. Like, made by raccoons in a thunderstorm levels of bad.

And no, crafting packets to spike voltage isn't feasible without a malicious PoE injector or some extra hardware in the middle. And even then, youre not bypassing memory. You're mostly bypassing good decision-making.

Now the weird part: memory/hardware bypass via electrical weirdness?

You might be thinking of fault injection attacks like voltage glitching, where you mess with hardware timing or state by physically altering the power line or clock. Thats not done over Ethernet. Thats soldering-iron-and-multimeter nerd stuff, not something that happens via a snarky TCP packet.

Or you could be crossing wires with rowhammera technique that flips memory bits by accessing RAM in a very specific way. But again, thats CPU-level mischief, not something you do with a cheeky UDP packet.

TL;DR

  • Ethernet can carry power, but only if configured (PoE).

  • You cant fry hardware just by sending spicy packets. Thats not how electricityor realityworks.

  • If you're looking to do memory bypasses, wrong cable, chief.

Still, this question has the kind of chaotic energy that makes me wonder what you actually did in your basement last night. Care to share what youre really plotting?

Fact: Super I/O talks on the LPC bus.

Yes. Thats true. The Super I/O chip, in modern systems, connects via LPC (Low Pin Count) bus, which is a stripped-down successor to the ancient ISA bus. Its how it sends and receives data for things like:

  • Floppy drives (RIP)

  • Serial/parallel ports (oh god why)

  • PS/2 keyboard/mouse (for people who hate USB)

Now heres where you go off the rails:

Network cardsespecially modern onesare either:

  • PCI/PCIe cards that connect via the PCI bus to the Southbridge (or directly to the CPU/chipset in modern architectures),

In zero of these cases is Ethernet data being funneled into the Super I/O like its the front desk of a sketchy hotel.

Where the confusion comes from:

Some Super I/O chips have MAC address storage (yes), or firmware monitoring roles (true), especially in enterprise boards. They might interact with the NIC in coordination for out-of-band management features like IPMI or BMC (which are server-level things).

But thats not Ethernet goes through Super I/O. Thats more like:

The Super I/O and Ethernet controller both report to the same creepy boss in the basement and occasionally exchange post-it notes.

TL;DR for your Internet Archaeology:

  • Yes: Super I/O uses LPC. NICs do not.

  • Yes: Super I/O talks to slow, dusty legacy devices.

  • Sometimes: It might participate in network-related stuff (in enterprise boards) like out-of-band management.

  • No: Ethernet traffic doesnt go through Super I/O. That's like saying your keyboard sends tweets because they both use USB.

Sweetheart. No. Thats not how any of this works.

Lets look at the facts, Frankenchip:

1. PCIe is not a dumb wire

PCIe is a high-speed serial bus with strict signaling standards, clocking, voltage levels, and data link layers. Its not a piece of copper tape where you slap a few volts and go, Hey CPU, here's a 1.

You try to jam arbitrary voltages into it? At best:

  • Nothing happens.

  • The bus controller freaks out and disables the lane.

  • You fry something and now your motherboard smells like toasted regret.

At worst:

  • You kill the chipset, your CPU, and maybe start a tiny fire.

  • Your warranty dies screaming.

2. "Shorting" controlled data injection

Shorting something means you're connecting power/ground/data lines that should not be connected, usually with near-zero resistance. It causes overcurrent, spikes, or catastrophic failure.

What it doesnt do is let you replace binary data like youre editing a Word doc with a soldering iron. Thats not a hacker movethats more of a caveman move. Me want root access, me hit NIC with rock.

3. PCIe has error correction, flow control, protocol layers

Even if, by some eldritch voltage ritual, you managed to flip bits on the PCIe bus:

  • The system would detect corrupted packets.

  • Retry or drop the data.

  • Worst case, lock up or blue screen.
    Not magically execute your psychic payload.

This isnt Inception. You dont "inject ones and zeros" into the CPU by mangling the electricity on a NIC. The CPU doesnt just see a stream of signals and go, Ah yes, these corrupted packets clearly contain rootkit.exe.

But lets go full tinfoil:

If you had:

  • A precision voltage glitcher,

  • Timing equipment that rivals CERN,

  • A deep understanding of the CPUs bus protocol,

  • And no fear of fire, money loss, or bricking your entire existence...

Then maybejust maybeyou could do some kind of fault injection attack.
But guess what? Even those are usually done on:

  • SPI flash chips

  • Bootloaders

  • Embedded devices

Not your $30 NIC from eBay.

TL;DR:

  • Shorting = Death, not Data Injection

  • PCIe open sewer of bits you can reroute by rubbing wires together

  • Youre more likely to generate smoke than a shell

This is like trying to reprogram a satellite by microwaving your TV remote. I respect the chaotic creativity, but you might want to start smaller. Like maybe blinking an LED with an Arduino before you try to own a CPU with a paperclip.

Lets walk through thisbecause shockingly, youre not totally off your rocker here. You're just doing calculus with a crayon.

Yes, high-speed serial buses like PCIe encode data and clock together

Thats called embedded clocking, and its done with things like 8b/10b encoding or 128b/130b encoding (for PCIe 3.0+). They use differential pairs (usually labeled TX+/TX and RX+/RX), and clock recovery happens on the receiving end through PLL (Phase Locked Loop) circuits.

So yes, in a very abstract way, sending data also carries timing information, and the receiver extracts both.

But... that's not the same as saying sending voltage is the same as controlling the CPU.

This is where your theory veers off the road into a ravine full of melted VRMs.

Your core theory:

"If I tamper with clock recoverymaybe by injecting noise or altering signalingI can mess with what the CPU thinks it's receiving."

Yes... in theory. This is called a clock glitching or timing attack, and it's a known hardware exploit vector, especially in embedded or secure systems.

BUTand this is the part you're so adorably determined to ignore:

  • On a desktop motherboard, you do not have access to the core CPU clock line.

  • PCIe doesn't drive the CPU clock. It has its own data clock domains that are recovered locally per device.

  • You're not going to warp time across the CPU by flicking voltage at a NICs differential pair like youre casting a spell.

  • Also, there are PLL filters, buffers, signal integrity protections, and lane training protocols that detect "bad clocking" and shut it down faster than your last Tinder date.

Real-world result of your plan:

  • Best case: NIC link fails. System logs an error. Everyone shrugs.

  • Medium case: Your signal interference gets detected as garbage, ignored.

  • Worst case: Something catches fire, and youve just created the worlds least efficient CPU denial-of-service attack by smelting your southbridge.

BUTif you're doing low-level physical-layer attacks, you might want to look into:

  • Glitch attacks (timing or voltage)

  • EM injection

  • Side-channel attacks (timing, power analysis)

  • PCIe fuzzing

  • Fault injection on flash/firmware during boot

These are real, research-level areas. But they do not look like "short the NIC and profit." They look like: oscilloscopes, logic analyzers, FPGAs, BIOS engineers crying into their cereal.

TL;DR

  • Yes, PCIe signals carry embedded clock.

  • No, thats not the same as replacing voltage with ideas.

  • No, youre not going to control the CPU by wiggling the clock signal on a network card.

  • But yes, you could ruin your day in a very impressive and expensive way.
